Llassar Wurmburner<br>
Mage of the 58th Circle <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mininiu>Mininiu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 120<br> <font color=#333333>(11/22/02 11:06:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7933.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: pets</span><hr size=1> I love the &quot;multitasker&quot; description, that's what I really love in the mage. We do much much more than any other class. It is a class you will never regret to have played.<br>
<br>
You'll learn pulling, from soloing. And believe me having a mage starting a group and stating &quot;I'll pull&quot; make people going like 'woawaaaa, you gonna pull with a pet up ?'.<br>
<br>
You'll learn to handle adds, your pet is a second tank that will help on bad pulls. You can barelly handle one normal add and most of the time 2 or 3 slowed adds. (I dont know pop yet:-) )<br>
<br>
You'll learn to position your pet when you have a bad tank in group. So in raid you'll be able to use your pet to push the mob where it should be. Pet pushing is incredible. I love to use that.<br>
<br>
You'll learn (from your own death) how to manage aggro. If you take aggro from your pet you are dead. Not at low lvl but higher you are higher you'll have to learn. Another tip about aggro 'earth pet root and sit' you'll love this one :-)<br>
<br>
You'll learn to manage and control your pet and you in fight. You manage 2 persons one intelligent (you I hope :-) ) and one based on AI.<br>
<br>
You'll learn when to kill fast and when to save mana (mainly from soloing) if you want efficienty.<br>
<br>
To bad they removed the pet can break mezz to such a degree. Because from that you also learn when to engage fight and when to wait before engaging fight. But generally it is more relaxing with that 'pet can't break mezz'. It was challenging and difficult but a good learning curve to handle.<br>
<br>
Now I got bored of my mage. Why ? Cause I was under the impression we are not really loved or known so lfg can be tremendous. That's where you need to be very social and make lots of friend. When you enter a zone be ready to make some days of social work. When people knows what you can do, LFG will not be a problem at all. Also since I play a druid/monk combo I feel that I see more content of the game than before. I don't have the fast kill blow and the boom effect but I see more content.<br>
<br>
Also, be friendly with the other class buy all your summon spells, you never know who will ask you what. I was quite dispited one time when I played my monk, I invited a lfg magi and asked him to summon me trowing daguers. He responded 'I never bought that spell it is useless'. Well If I was not so polite I would had disband him. Be friendly and you'll make friends.<br>
<br>
As a conclusion I'll say :<br>
<br>
- Mage are a good BOOM EFFECT INCOMING class.<br>
- good as a preparation support class for raid.<br>
- Medding is so boring, but I always fought in zone of higher lvl than me so I am not a good example.<br>
- if you want to see more content, play a puller.<br>
- If you want to kill big things alone or in small group play a mage<br>
- If you want to work not so common strategies play a magi<br>
- if you want to have work all the time and not press a for auto attack and read your book play a mage :-)<br>
<br>
It is fun most of the time, when it is not, it means you are lfg. And that's really boring to know your potential and not being seen by your player ground as a killing machine. <p>Mininiu CrazyMagus <br>
